Task: How do I require an async closure type&#39;s future to be Send?

 <p>What is the appropriate way for me to express the trait bounds on the following function?</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>/// Accept a closure type H such that:
///
/// *   H can be called repeatedly with an i32 input.
/// *   H returns a future type F.
/// *   F is Send.
/// *   F's output is Send.
/// *   H itself need not be Send.
/// 
fn register_handler&lt;H&gt;(handler: H) /* where H: ??? */ { todo!(); }
</code></pre>
<p>I believe the following captures <em>most</em> of this:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>fn register_handler&lt;H, R&gt;(handler: H)
where
    H: AsyncFn(i32) -&gt; R,
    R: Send,
{
    todo!();
}
</code></pre>
<p>However this requires only that the result be <code>Send</code>, not the future. The best I can come up with to capture that is the following:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>fn register_handler&lt;H, F, R&gt;(handler: H)
where
    H: Fn(i32) -&gt; F,
    F: Future&lt;Output = R&gt; + Send,
    R: Send,
{
    todo!();
}
</code></pre>
<p>This <em>seems</em> to be correct, but spelling the bound this way rather than using <code>AsyncFn</code> seems to <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/79883421/what-does-an-implementation-of-fnonce-is-not-general-enough-error-mean?noredirect=1#comment140972275_79883421">interact poorly</a> with other language features. I don't know how to spell it with <code>AsyncFn</code>, since I believe I'd be requiring that <code>H</code> itself be <code>Send</code>, not its result future type.</p>


