Task: How to pass a set of mutable vectors to a callback repeatedly?

 <p>I would like to implement the following flow:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Collect list of mutable vectors based on various conditions.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Pass the list to a callback which can mutate values of these vectors (but not vectors themselves, i.e. it cannot add/remove items.)</p>
<ul>
<li>References of these vectors are not supposed to be stored anywhere by the callback. I.e. they're borrowed only for the duration of single callback execution.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>Use this list repeatedly (i.e. it's a buffer.)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Ideally, it should be implemented as an iterator, but that seems to be impossible in Rust, so my attempt uses for-each method with a FnMut callback.</p>
<p>Here's my (very simplified and as short as I could make it) best attempt, which, however, doesn't compile, because, as far as I understand, the borrow checker thinks the buffer remains borrowed to the callback after its execution:</p>
<pre><code>use std::{
    cell::{RefCell, RefMut},
    collections::HashMap,
};

struct Component {
    // Some parameters which needs to be mutated.
}

/// A portion of data to be mutated.
struct Foo {
    /// Number of items in all vectors in the components map.
    size: usize,

    /// Each vector can be considered a &quot;column&quot;.
    /// A &quot;row&quot; is defined as components from all vectors at a particular index.
    components: HashMap&lt;usize, RefCell&lt;Vec&lt;Component&gt;&gt;&gt;,
}

/// This encapsulates data passed to the callback.
struct InstanceRef&lt;'a&gt; {
    index: usize,
    component_iter: std::slice::IterMut&lt;'a, RefMut&lt;'a, Vec&lt;Component&gt;&gt;&gt;,
}

impl&lt;'a&gt; InstanceRef&lt;'a&gt; {
    fn next_component(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Option&lt;&amp;mut Component&gt; {
        // In real app, this is a bit more involved - stored data is Any
        // and it's cast to the concrete type here.
        self.component_iter
            .next()
            .and_then(|a| a.get_mut(self.index))
    }
}

/// Set of all data.
struct WorldOfFoo {
    foos: Vec&lt;Foo&gt;,
}

impl WorldOfFoo {
    /// This is the problematic method. Execute the callback for all Foo
    /// instances which has all the required component types. The callback 
    /// should be called for each Component row and it doesn't need to
    /// know about Foo instances.
    fn for_each_foo_with_components&lt;T&gt;(&amp;self, component_types: &amp;[usize], mut callback: T)
    where
        T: FnMut(InstanceRef),
    {
        // The buffer. It's *very* undesired to allocate it every single iteration.
        let mut components_buffer: Vec&lt;RefMut&lt;Vec&lt;Component&gt;&gt;&gt; =
            Vec::with_capacity(component_types.len());

        // (In real code, there's some filtering here to speed up.)
        // This is semi-hot code (but still by order of magnitude less
        // than the inner loop.)
        'foos: for foo in &amp;self.foos {
            // Collect references to all desired components of Foo
            // and filter out ones which don't have them all.
            // Obviously, each component type needs to be unique.
            for ctype in component_types {
                if let Some(components) = foo.components.get(ctype) {
                    components_buffer.push(components.try_borrow_mut().unwrap());
                } else {
                    // This foo doesn't have all the needed types
                    // -&gt; don't want to visit this instance.
                    continue 'foos;
                }
            }

            // This is the hot code. The size can be really big.
            // (Also, the range is a bit more complicated in the real code.)
            for index in 0..foo.size {
                // What's needed here is to pass all the components at
                // the index position as mutable.
                callback(InstanceRef {
                    index,
                    // This triggers the first error (see below):
                    component_iter: components_buffer.iter_mut(),
                });
            }

            // This triggers the second error:
            components_buffer = clear_vector(components_buffer);
        }
    }
}

fn example(world: &amp;WorldOfFoo) {
    let component_types = [4, 8, 15, 16, 23, 42];
    world.for_each_foo_with_components(&amp;component_types, |mut instance_ref| {
        let _a: &amp;mut Component = instance_ref.next_component().unwrap();
        let _b: &amp;mut Component = instance_ref.next_component().unwrap();
        let _c: &amp;mut Component = instance_ref.next_component().unwrap();

        // Here a, b, and c can be mutated.
        // Their references are not supposed to be stored outside this scope.
    });
}

/// A hack to drop borrows by a vector.
///
/// - https://users.rust-lang.org/t/clearing-vec-doesnt-drop-the-borrow/124288
/// - https://users.rust-lang.org/t/reused-vec-in-loop/134116
pub fn clear_vector&lt;T, U&gt;(mut v: Vec&lt;T&gt;) -&gt; Vec&lt;U&gt; {
    // There doesn't seem to be a way to check this at compile-time, so assert at runtime.
    assert_eq!((size_of::&lt;T&gt;() * v.capacity()) % size_of::&lt;U&gt;(), 0);
    assert_eq!(align_of::&lt;T&gt;(), align_of::&lt;U&gt;());

    v.clear();

    // Note that this uses knowledge about the implementation which makes it technically incorrect.
    v.into_iter() // Supposedly, this moves the memory to the iterator.
        .map(|_| unreachable!()) // &quot;Convert&quot; types, but the vector is empty.
        .collect() // Supposedly, this reuses the memory as long as T and U are compatible.
}
</code></pre>
<p>The errors:</p>
<pre><code>error[E0499]: cannot borrow `components_buffer` as mutable more than once at a time
   --&gt; my_test.rs:393:41
