<li><p>The <code>InstanceRef</code> is there to simplify passing the data. In real code, there are some meta-data and actually two arrays with components - the other one contains immutable references (the mutable ones are usually calculated using properties from the immutable ones), but that's not important for the main issue.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>It stores an iterator because I couldn't figure any other way how to assure that the callback can get only single mutable reference of each component satisfying borrow checker rules.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Note that in real code, components are stored as <code>Any</code> and then cast to appropriate type by the callback.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>


