Task: Rust and C++ FFI: orchestrating destructors/drops of struct fields

 <p>Because of some FFI code interacting with C++ I need precise manual control on when the <code>Drop::drop()</code> method of types is called w.r.t. those of fields.</p>
<p>To be more precise:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>When a C++ struct is destroyed, the destructor is called (<code>T::~T()</code>) and then the fields are destructed in <em>reverse</em> declaration order.</p>
</li>
<li><p>When a Rust struct is dropped, <code>Drop::drop()</code> is called, and then the fields are dropped in <em>declaration order</em>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>If we ignore the different drop order of the fields the mechanisms are quite similar, so <code>T::~T()</code> in C++ has the role of <code>Drop::drop()</code> in Rust.</p>
<p>So suppose I have a struct in Rust:</p>
<pre><code>#[repr(C)]
pub struct MyStruct {
   field: AnotherStruct
}

#[repr(C)]
pub struct AnotherStruct {
   something: *mut i32
}

impl Drop for MyStruct {
   // ...
}

impl Drop for AnotherStruct {
   // ...
}
</code></pre>
<p>On the C++ side I can declare the structs as follows:</p>
<pre><code>struct AnotherStruct {
    int32_t *something;

    ~AnotherStruct() {
        // what to put here
    }
};

struct MyStruct {
    AnotherStruct field;

    ~MyStruct() {
        // what to put here
    }
};
</code></pre>
<p>Now, being <code>#[repr(C)]</code> I can pass the structs by value to an <code>extern &quot;C&quot;</code> function:</p>
<p>Rust:</p>
<pre><code>unsafe extern &quot;C&quot; {
   pub fn test(object: MyStruct);
}
</code></pre>
<p>C++:</p>
<pre><code>extern &quot;C&quot; {
   void test(MyStruct object) {
      // use `object`...
   }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Now the problem though is that to avoid leaks etc. I need to fill the destructors of the two C++ structs above.</p>
<p>Ideally from C++ I should:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>call <code>MyStruct::drop()</code>  in <code>MyStruct::~MyStruct()</code></p>
</li>
<li><p>let C++ call the destructor of <code>field</code></p>
</li>
<li><p>call <code>AnotherStruct::drop()</code> in <code>AnotherStruct::~AnotherStruct()</code></p>
</li>
<li><p>let C++ call the destructor of <code>ptr</code> (which is a no-op).</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Note that in step 1 I cannot use <code>std::ptr::drop_in_place()</code> because dropping <code>MyStruct</code> completely would drop its field as well, but later C++ would call the destructor of <code>field</code> again.</p>
<p>So I need to intentionally ignore executing the drop glue on the Rust side. However, it seems there is no way of calling <code>Drop::drop()</code> in Rust without the glue.</p>
<p>Note that the problem applies only because I'm trying to move a struct out to an <code>extern &quot;C&quot;</code> function. If I pass things by reference I can use <code>std::ptr::drop_in_place()</code> freely because C++ destructors will not run at all. But that's exactly what I want/need to do.</p>
<p>Some apparent solutions are not viable for me, in particular:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>I cannot change the API of the Rust structs I'm exporting so I cannot change <code>field: AnotherStruct</code> for <code>field: ManuallyDrop&lt;AnotherStruct&gt;</code></p>
</li>
<li><p>On the C++ side I may avoid the field's destructors to run by wrapping the field in a union, such as:<br />
<code>struct MyStruct {</code><br />
<code>   union { AnotherStruct field; } field_u;</code><br />
<code>};</code><br />
but then I would need to use the field as <code>object.field_u.field</code> instead of <code>object.field</code> and I need to avoid that.
<strong>Edit:</strong> see in the answer how this can be solved.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>So is there any way out of this problem?</p>


