Task: Allow mutable borrow alongside immutable borrow in Rust

 <p>The Rust compiler doesn't allow the following code to compile. This is because the <code>for</code> loop which calls <code>thing.get_prefixes()</code> creates an immutable reference to <code>thing</code>, and during the loop body the compiler is correctly detecting that a mutable reference to <code>thing</code> is required by the call to <code>thing.add_phrase()</code>.</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>struct Thing {
    prefixes: Vec&lt;String&gt;,
    phrases: Vec&lt;String&gt;,
}

impl Thing {
    pub fn new(prefixes: Vec&lt;String&gt;) -&gt; Thing {
        Thing {
            prefixes,
            phrases: Vec::new(),
        }
    }

    pub fn get_prefixes(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;Vec&lt;String&gt; {
        &amp;self.prefixes
    }

    pub fn add_phrase(&amp;mut self, phrase: String) {
        self.phrases.push(phrase);
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut thing = Thing::new(vec![String::from(&quot;abc&quot;)]);

    for prefix in thing.get_prefixes() {
        let mut phrase: String = prefix.to_owned();
        phrase.push_str(&quot;123&quot;);
        thing.add_phrase(phrase);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>The following is the compiler error:</p>
<pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code>error[E0502]: cannot borrow `thing` as mutable because it is also borrowed as immutable
  --&gt; src/main.rs:29:9
   |
26 |     for prefix in thing.get_prefixes() {
   |                   --------------------
   |                   |
   |                   immutable borrow occurs here
   |                   immutable borrow later used here
...
29 |         thing.add_phrase(phrase);
   |         ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ mutable borrow occurs here
</code></pre>
<p>This makes perfect sense.</p>
<p>However I believe the code <em>would</em> be safe to execute because the loop condition uses the <code>prefixes</code> attribute of the <code>Thing</code> instance, the loop body is modifying the <code>phrases</code> attribute of the instance. So in <em>this specific case</em>, there is no overwriting of the same data, or trying to read data after it was freed, etc.</p>
<p>My understanding is that the compiler error is raised because borrow checking is made against the same point of reference in the loop conditional and in the loop body; the <code>thing</code> instance of <code>Thing</code>. Is it not fine grained enough to create a borrow reference against an attribute of an object, only the object in its entirety.</p>
<p>Is it possible to somehow give the compiler a hint, that two different attributes are being referenced separately? Or to somehow help the borrow checker see that the entire object isn't being modified, only a specific attribute? Or is this just a limitation of Rust?</p>
