Task: Can I have a reference to a variable while still allowing that variable to be mutated in Rust?

 <p>Is there a way that I can have a reference to a variable while allowing that variable to be mutated in Rust, so long as I &quot;pinky promise not to access the data of the stored variable&quot; so that I don't actually care about the underlying value being mutated?</p>
<p>Here is my use case. I'm working on a way to use variables as &quot;labels&quot; or unique keys by creating ids. My current solution is to have an <code>IdGenerator</code> that has an incrementing index that is used to set the Id's stored value:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>struct IdGenerator
{
    idx: usize
}

impl IdGenerator
{
    pub fn id(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Id
    {
        let old_id = self.idx;
        self.idx += 1;
        Id
        {
            id: old_id
        }
    }
}

struct Id
{
    id: usize
}
</code></pre>
<p>However, I would like Ids generated from different generators to equal false to each other. In order to do this, I store a reference to the IdGenerator. However, I run into various issues when I try this:</p>
<p>1. My first attempt is to store a reference to the IdGenerator. I don't actually need the value of IdGenerator, I just need to know where it's stored so I can know which IdGenerator created it.</p>
<pre><code>struct Id&lt;'a&gt;
{
    id: usize,
    ref: &amp;'a IdGenerator
}

impl PartialEq for Id&lt;'a&gt;
{
    fn eq(&amp;self, other: &amp;Self) -&gt; bool
    {
        // Casting to a pointer here bc I want the address of IdGenerator, I don't actually care about the value.
        self.id == other.id &amp;&amp; (self.ref as *const IdGenerator) == (other.ref as *const IdGenerator)
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>But of course, I can't mutate IdGenerator while storing a reference to an Id like this.</p>
<p>2. Since I only need the address of IdGenerator, I don't have to store it as a reference, I can just use a pointer.</p>
<pre><code>struct Id
{
    id: usize,
    addr: *const IdGenerator,
}

impl IdGenerator
{
    pub fn id(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Id
    {
        let old_id = self.idx;
        self.idx += 1;
        Id
        {
            id: old_id,
            addr: (self as *const IdGenerator)
        }
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>The problem with this is that I lose the ability to tie the lifetime of the Id to the object that created it. With this version I can do something like this:</p>
<pre><code>let bad_id = {
    let mut id_generator = IdGenerator::new();
    id_generator.id()
};
</code></pre>
<p>Here <code>bad_id</code> outlives the <code>IdGenerator</code> that created it. This is <em>probably</em> fine, but there's a small but non-zero chance that, later, a new <code>Id</code> is generated by a different <code>IdGenerator</code> that happens to have the same memory address, resulting in false truthiness when comparing the two <code>Id</code>s.</p>
<p>I wish I could tell the Rust compiler &quot;an <code>Id</code> can't live outside of the <code>IdGenerator</code> that created it's scope, but it's fine to mutate the <code>IdGenerator</code> since an Id doesn't actually ever use or access the <code>IdGenerator</code>'s data&quot;. Am I misunderstanding the purpose of forbidding simultaneous mutable and immutable references for my use case?</p>
<p>I'm aware that there are many possible workarounds to this. I could allow interior mutability on the <code>IdGenerator</code>, I could use an <code>Rc</code> to track references to the <code>IdGenerator</code>, or I could use some sort of static variable to increment the <code>idx</code> instead of a generator. I'm also aware that using a memory address as a UUID substitute is <em>probably</em> a bad idea anyways. But for the sake of argument and understanding, what would I have to do to get this working if at all possible? How can I have my cake and eat it too, getting the benefit of lifetimes for logical reasoning and invariance without preventing a mutable reference to an <code>IdGenerator</code>?</p>


