Task: Why CPU-Bound Work should not run on Tokio’s I/O Executor

 <p>Why is the blocking thread pool (spawn_blocking) better suited for CPU-heavy work than the I/O executor threads, even if my runtime has many worker threads?</p>
<p>In the example, both IO executor and CPU executor take the same amount of time to run the blocking IO tasks.</p>
<p><a href="https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2024&amp;gist=bc1bcb424ba89f33af3ab509dc83033c" rel="nofollow noreferrer">https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2024&amp;gist=bc1bcb424ba89f33af3ab509dc83033c</a></p>
<pre><code>
use tokio::time::Instant;
use std::hint::black_box;


fn blocking_call() {
    // Synchronous blocking call - this will hold a thread hostage
    std::thread::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(1000));
}


#[tokio::main(flavor = &quot;multi_thread&quot;, worker_threads = 8)]
async fn main() {
    let n = 8;

    // ----------------------------------------------
    // 1. tokio::spawn with blocking code (BAD - blocks worker threads!)
    // ----------------------------------------------
    let start = Instant::now();

    let handles: Vec&lt;_&gt; =
        (0..n).map(|_| tokio::spawn(async move { blocking_call() })).collect();

    for h in handles {
        h.await.unwrap();
    }

    println!(&quot;tokio::spawn + blocking code took {:?}&quot;, start.elapsed());


    let start = Instant::now();

    let handles: Vec&lt;_&gt; =
        (0..n).map(|_| tokio::task::spawn_blocking(|| {
            blocking_call()

        })).collect();

    for h in handles {
        h.await.unwrap();
    }

    println!(&quot;spawn_blocking + io_work took {:?}&quot;, start.elapsed());
}
</code></pre>


