Task: How can a function accept a collection of FnOnce closures of disparate types without boxing them?

 <p>What is the correct way for a function to accept a collection of functions that it promises to call only once, where the functions may be of disparate concrete types? I'd like to do the following, which makes it easy to call the function with an array of closures:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>fn f(fs: &amp;[&amp;dyn FnOnce()]) {
    todo!();
}

fn g() {
    f(&amp;[&amp;|| {}, &amp;|| {}]);
}
</code></pre>
<p>This works, but the problem is that <code>f</code> can't actually call its input functions because it has only references and <code>FnOnce</code> <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/ops/trait.FnOnce.html#tymethod.call_once" rel="nofollow noreferrer">requires handing over ownership</a>. Is there any way to do better than accepting <code>Vec&lt;Box&lt;dyn FnOnce()&gt;&gt;</code> and forcing the user's call site to be extra cumbersome?</p>


