Task: A repository generic over an sqlx executor in Rust

 <p>There's a use case in my application where I need to write to 2 repositories and make sure that either both of the writes succeed or neither of them does. To be more precise, it's the user registration process: the <code>UserService</code>'s <code>register_user</code> method must save the actual user (<code>UserRepository.save</code>) and also create a <code>Participant</code> instance for it and save this new participant aggregate using the <code>ParticipantRepository.save</code> method. For the sakes of data correctness I've decided to use the UoW pattern, so the resulting <code>UserService.register_user</code> method's code looks like this:</p>
<pre><code>    async fn register_user(
        &amp;self,
        register_user_data: RegisterUserData,
    ) -&gt; Result&lt;User, Self::Error&gt; {
        let mut tx = self.user_registration_uow_provider.begin().await?;

        let participant_id = ParticipantId::new();
        let user_id = UserId::new();

        let associated_participant = Participant::builder()
            .id(participant_id)
            .name(register_user_data.name.clone())
            .user_id(Some(user_id))
            .build()
            .validate()?;

        let user = User::builder()
            .id(user_id)
            .name(register_user_data.name)
            .participant_id(participant_id)
            .build()
            .validate()?;

        let saved_user = tx.user_repo().save(user).await?;
        tx.participant_repo().save(associated_participant).await?;

        tx.commit().await?;

        Ok(saved_user)
    }
</code></pre>
<p>First, I'm creating a transaction by calling the <code>UserRegistrationUoWProvider</code>'s <code>begin</code> method, and then using this transaction I get access to both the required repositories (User and Participant) to later commit the transaction, so that I could rest assured there'd be no case when only the User info is saved and no Participant is created for it (or vice-versa).</p>
<p>For reference, the <code>UserService</code> trait is defined like this:</p>
<pre><code>#[trait_variant::make(Send)]
#[auto_impl(Arc)]
pub trait UserService {
    type Error: UserServiceError;

    /// Creates a user using the provided user registration DTO.
    ///
    /// This will also create a `Participant` and associate it with the created user.
    async fn register_user(
        &amp;self,
        register_user_data: RegisterUserData,
    ) -&gt; Result&lt;User, Self::Error&gt;;
}
</code></pre>
<p>Now, there's 2 UoW-related traits: <code>UserRegistrationUnitOfWork</code> and its <code>UserRegistrationUoWProvider</code>:</p>
<pre><code>#[trait_variant::make(Send)]
pub trait UserRegistrationUnitOfWork&lt;'uow&gt;: Send + Sync + 'uow {
    type Error: RepositoryError + Send + Sync + 'static;
    type ParticipantRepo&lt;'a&gt;: ParticipantRepository&lt;Error = Self::Error&gt; + Sync + 'a
    where
        Self: 'a;
    type UserRepo&lt;'a&gt;: UserRepository&lt;Error = Self::Error&gt; + Sync + 'a
    where
        Self: 'a;

    fn participant_repo&lt;'a&gt;(&amp;'a mut self) -&gt; Self::ParticipantRepo&lt;'a&gt;;
    fn user_repo&lt;'a&gt;(&amp;'a mut self) -&gt; Self::UserRepo&lt;'a&gt;;

    async fn commit(self) -&gt; Result&lt;(), Self::Error&gt;;
    async fn rollback(self) -&gt; Result&lt;(), Self::Error&gt;;
}

#[trait_variant::make(Send)]
pub trait UserRegistrationUoWProvider: Send + Sync + 'static {
    type Error: RepositoryError + Send + Sync + 'static;
    type UoW&lt;'a&gt;: UserRegistrationUnitOfWork&lt;'a, Error = Self::Error&gt; + Send + Sync + 'a
    where
        Self: 'a;

    async fn begin&lt;'a&gt;(&amp;'a self) -&gt; Result&lt;Self::UoW&lt;'a&gt;, Self::Error&gt;;
}
</code></pre>
<p>There's too much stuff going on regarding lifetimes, and here I must explain that <strong>all the code I share here is (what I believe to be) the closest attempt to just make it work</strong>. It's definitely possible that everything is overly-complicated, and I would happily accept answers which explain how to achieve what I'm looking for in a more reasonable manner.</p>
<p>Now, to the repos. Both the <code>UserRepository</code> and <code>ParticipantRepository</code> are implemented pretty much the same (I use SQLite), so I'm only gonna show the <code>UserRepository</code> implementation code here:</p>
<pre><code>pub struct SqliteUserRepository&lt;'e, E&gt;
where
    for&lt;'c&gt; &amp;'c E: Executor&lt;'c, Database = Sqlite&gt;,
    E: Send + Sync,
{
    exec: &amp;'e E,
}

impl&lt;'e, E&gt; SqliteUserRepository&lt;'e, E&gt;
where
    for&lt;'c&gt; &amp;'c E: Executor&lt;'c, Database = Sqlite&gt;,
    E: Send + Sync,
{
    pub fn new(exec: &amp;'e E) -&gt; Self {
        SqliteUserRepository { exec }
    }
}

impl&lt;'e, E&gt; UserRepository for SqliteUserRepository&lt;'e, E&gt;
where
    for&lt;'c&gt; &amp;'c E: Executor&lt;'c, Database = Sqlite&gt;,
    E: Send + Sync,
{
    type Error = SqliteRepositoryError;

    #[instrument(
        level = &quot;debug&quot;,
        skip(self, user),
        name = &quot;Repo::user::save&quot;,
        fields(user_id = %user.id())
    )]
    async fn save(&amp;self, user: User) -&gt; Result&lt;User, Self::Error&gt; {
        let id = user.id().to_string();
        let name = user.name();
        let participant_id = user.participant_id().to_string();

        sqlx::query!(
            &quot;INSERT INTO users (id, name, participant_id) VALUES (?, ?, ?)&quot;,
            id,
            name,
            participant_id
        )
        .execute(self.exec)
        .await?;

        Ok(user)
    }
</code></pre>
<p><strong>My goal is to make my repositories to be generic over any sqlx executor</strong>. Namely, what I care about is <code>&amp;SqlitePool</code> and <code>&amp;mut SqliteTransaction</code>. If I finally succeed to implement all this code correctly, then the usage can look like this:</p>
<pre><code>// main.rs - the composition root

    // I can instantiate standalone repos which use the connection pool directly.
    let participant_repo = Arc::new(SqliteParticipantRepository::new(&amp;pool));
    let user_repo = Arc::new(SqliteUserRepository::new(&amp;pool));

    // Here how I'd use them (in other services).
    let group_service = Arc::new(GroupServiceImpl::new(
        Arc::clone(&amp;expense_repo),
        Arc::clone(&amp;group_repo),
        Arc::clone(&amp;participant_repo),
        Arc::clone(&amp;user_repo),
        BalanceServiceImpl::new(),
        SettlementServiceImpl::new(),
    ));

    // And then for the user service, I should be able to instantiate the `UserRegistrationUoWProvider` so that it becomes responsible for creating the actual user registration UoW (with access to the User and Participant) repos.
    let user_registration_uow_provider = SqliteUserRegistrationUoWProvider::new(pool.clone());
    let user_service = Arc::new(UserServiceImpl::new(user_registration_uow_provider));
</code></pre>
<p>And I think what remains is to show the implementation for the UoW and its provider:</p>
<pre><code>pub struct SqliteUserRegistrationUnitOfWork&lt;'tx&gt; {
    tx: Transaction&lt;'tx, Sqlite&gt;,
}

impl&lt;'tx&gt; SqliteUserRegistrationUnitOfWork&lt;'tx&gt; {
    pub fn new(tx: Transaction&lt;'tx, Sqlite&gt;) -&gt; Self {
        Self { tx }
    }
}

impl&lt;'uow&gt; UserRegistrationUnitOfWork&lt;'uow&gt; for SqliteUserRegistrationUnitOfWork&lt;'uow&gt; {
    type Error = SqliteRepositoryError;
    type ParticipantRepo&lt;'a&gt;
        = SqliteParticipantRepository&lt;'a, Transaction&lt;'uow, Sqlite&gt;&gt;
    where
