    fn participant_repo(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Self::ParticipantRepo {
        SqliteParticipantRepository::new(&amp;mut self.tx)
    }
    fn user_repo(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Self::UserRepo {
        SqliteUserRepository::new(&amp;mut self.tx)
    }

    async fn commit(self) -&gt; Result&lt;(), Self::Error&gt; {
        self.tx.commit().await?;
        Ok(())
    }
    async fn rollback(self) -&gt; Result&lt;(), Self::Error&gt; {
        self.tx.rollback().await?;
        Ok(())
    }
}

pub struct SqliteUserRegistrationUoWProvider {
    pool: Pool&lt;Sqlite&gt;,
}

impl SqliteUserRegistrationUoWProvider {
    pub fn new(pool: Pool&lt;Sqlite&gt;) -&gt; Self {
        Self { pool }
    }
}

impl UserRegistrationUoWProvider for SqliteUserRegistrationUoWProvider {
    type Error = SqliteRepositoryError;

    type UoW&lt;'a&gt;
        = SqliteUserRegistrationUnitOfWork&lt;'a&gt;
    where
        Self: 'a;

    async fn begin&lt;'a&gt;(&amp;'a self) -&gt; Result&lt;Self::UoW&lt;'a&gt;, Self::Error&gt; {
        let tx = self.pool.begin().await?;
        Ok(SqliteUserRegistrationUnitOfWork::new(tx))
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Now to <strong>the issue</strong>: this whole code <em>almost</em> compiles. There's just one single point which fails to compile and produces the error which I show below:</p>
<pre><code>    async fn register_user(
        &amp;self,
        register_user_data: RegisterUserData,
    ) -&gt; Result&lt;User, Self::Error&gt; {
</code></pre>
<p>This line gives me the following error:</p>
<pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code>error: lifetime bound not satisfied
  --&gt; kip-core/src/application/services/user_service.rs:54:5
   |
54 | /     async fn register_user(
55 | |         &amp;self,
56 | |         register_user_data: RegisterUserData,
57 | |     ) -&gt; Result&lt;User, Self::Error&gt; {
   | |__________________________________^
   |
   = note: this is a known limitation that will be removed in the future (see issue #100013 &lt;https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/100013&gt; for more information)

</code></pre>
<p>In my attempts to fix it I, of course, followed the link to the mentioned GitHub issue, and not that I understood what's going on there well. I understand that this is some (temporal?) compiler limitation. But when will it be fixed? Someone suggested to use the nightly compiler with some feature flag, but doing so just creates a dozen more compiler errors.</p>
<p>I also found an idea to replace the <code>trait_variant</code> with <code>async_trait</code>, and I tried it (even though I dont like the boxed futures and dynamic dispatch idea), which also led to the very same line of code failing the compilation (but with some different errors this time).</p>
<p>The <code>sqlx</code> docs mention 2 things: 1st, there's the <code>Acquire</code> trait, but I think it's not suitable for me since the methods then will have to decide on their own somehow, whether to begin a transaction or aqcuire a connection, and this is something I want to avoid (I instead want the repository to be generic over whatever executor I can give it, so that the methods wouldn't have to decide themselves which exact executor to use/acquire). The second thing is that there are some examples in the docs of making <em>functions</em> generic over any executor, but this is not exactly what I want. I think that my case is different (and is harder) because I want to store that executor on the repository instance and to be able to re use it in methods.</p>
<p>All of this, and the absence (or maybe my inability?) to find any existing code examples for my specific situation also makes me think that maybe I chose an incorrect approach in the first place? Or maybe I shouldn't use sqlx?</p>
<p>Generally, I'm open to any ideas. A preferable answer should include some steps on finalizaing the code I've already written. But if what I'm trying to achieve isn't possible, I'd be happy to consider completely other approaches to what I'm doing.</p>


