Task: Is it possible to bound type-level recursion?

 <p>I'm trying to construct a typed lambda calculus, something along the lines of:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>struct Fun&lt;T&gt;(T); // actual definition elided for simplicity
struct TypeErasedExpr { /* elided for simplicity */ }
enum Expr&lt;T&gt; {
    Just(T),
    Apply(Box&lt;Expr&lt;Fun&lt;T&gt;&gt;, TypeErasedExpr),
}
</code></pre>
<p>Unfortunately, any functions that recurse over Expr lead to a compile-time stack overflow, because the compiler has to monomorphize <code>Expr&lt;T&gt;, Expr&lt;Fun&lt;T&gt;&gt;, Expr&lt;Fun&lt;Fun&lt;T&gt;&gt;&gt;, ...</code>. There's no way to tell the compiler &quot;just stop at this point&quot;.</p>
<p>I found a way to express this using associated types:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>enum Void {}
struct Succ&lt;N&gt;(N);
struct Fun&lt;T&gt;(T);
enum Expr&lt;T: Ladder&gt; {
    Just(T),
    Call(Box&lt;Expr&lt;T::Up&gt;&gt;),
}

trait Fuel {
    type Burn: Fuel;
    type Gate&lt;T: Ladder&gt;: Ladder;
}
impl Fuel for Void {
    type Burn = Void;
    type Gate&lt;T: Ladder&gt; = Void;
}
impl&lt;N: Fuel&gt; Fuel for Succ&lt;N&gt; {
    type Burn = N;
    type Gate&lt;T: Ladder&gt; = T;
}

trait Ladder {
    type Fuel: Fuel;
    type Up: Ladder;
}

impl Ladder for () {
    type Fuel = Succ&lt;Succ&lt;Succ&lt;Void&gt;&gt;&gt;;
    type Up = Fun&lt;Self&gt;;
}
// Fuel::Gate required because rust doesn't recognize `Succ&lt;N&gt;` and `Void` as disjoint
// implementations, so we can't do two seperately parameterized blanket implementations for Fun&lt;T&gt;
impl&lt;T: Ladder&gt; Ladder for Fun&lt;T&gt; {
    type Fuel = &lt;T::Fuel as Fuel&gt;::Burn;
    type Up = &lt;T::Fuel as Fuel&gt;::Gate&lt;Fun&lt;Self&gt;&gt;;
}
impl Ladder for Void {
    type Fuel = Void;
    type Up = Void;
}

impl&lt;T: Ladder&gt; Expr&lt;T&gt; {
    fn depth(&amp;self) -&gt; usize {
        match self {
            Self::Just(_) =&gt; 0,
            Self::Call(r) =&gt; 1 + r.depth(),
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    // Force monomorphization to expose compile errors
    let e = Expr::Just(Fun(Fun(())));
    let e = Expr::&lt;Fun&lt;()&gt;&gt;::Call(Box::new(e));
    let e = Expr::&lt;()&gt;::Call(Box::new(e));
    println!(&quot;{}&quot;, e.depth())
}
</code></pre>
<p>By constraining it with fuel, <code>Up</code> eventually eventually gets stuck in a loop, which the compiler is happy with: recursion with the same value is accepted, just not an infinitely growing type.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, this requires a seperate <code>Ladder</code> impl for every possible base <code>T</code>, as a blanket impl for T can't exclude Fun or be overridden by a Fun (I think? unless there's some way to express a <code>U exists such that T = Fun&lt;U&gt;</code>).
And a seperate <code>Fuel</code> trait definition for every possible type/trait pair (in our case <code>Fun/Ladder</code>).</p>
<p>I tried creating a downwards trait, that is implemented for <code>Fun&lt;Fun&lt;Fun&lt;T&gt;&gt;&gt;, which then descends down with a blank impl, and generates </code>Ladder` implementations with a blanket impl.
I also tried creating a kind of type-level ternary operator, but couldn't wrap my head around either of these solutions enough to make the compiler happy.
Is this possible?</p>


