Task: What API design choices exist for a struct that must be pinned?

 <p>Let's say we have a struct that needs address stability for some reason, for example it has a background thread that shares references to its internal state as in <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/a/79791894/1505451">this answer</a>. As a matter of API design, what options do we have for enforcing this? Are there options that don't force an extra allocation or use of <code>MaybeUninit</code> on the user of the API?</p>
<hr />
<p>To see what I mean about allocations and <code>MaybeUninit</code>:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>We could force the struct to be accessed only through pinned pointers by having its factory function return a pinned pointer itself. But it needs to be an owning pointer:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>pub struct Foo {
    _pin: std::marker::PhantomPinned,
}

impl Foo {
    // The factory function forces pinning (good), but chooses Box for ownership
    // on behalf of the caller (not good).
    pub fn new() -&gt; Pin&lt;Box&lt;Foo&gt;&gt; {
        todo!()
    }

    // Later when the user wants to actually use the struct they have to use a
    // pinned reference, as desired.
    pub fn do_something(self: Pin&lt;&amp;Foo&gt;) {
        todo!();
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>The use of <code>Box</code> forces the <code>Foo</code> to be its own allocation on the heap. This is unfortunate if the user wants to embed it within another pinned struct, where the extra allocation is otherwise unnecessary.</p>
</li>
<li><p>We could change things so the only way to create the struct is to emplace it into memory that is already pinned:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>pub struct Bar {
    _pin: std::marker::PhantomPinned,
}

impl Bar {
    // The factory function accepts the location into which to construct the Bar
    // object, forcing it to be pinned from the start (good) and avoiding
    // forcing an extra allocation for Box (good), but we also force the use of
    // MaybeUninit (less good).
    pub fn emplace(_target: Pin&lt;&amp;mut MaybeUninit&lt;Bar&gt;&gt;) {
        todo!()
    }

    // Later when the user wants to actually use the struct they have to use a
    // pinned reference, as desired.
    pub fn do_something(self: Pin&lt;&amp;Bar&gt;) {
        todo!();
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>I believe this API can be used soundly, but it's error prone. More importantly it also forces the caller to have to use <code>MaybeUninit</code>. It seems like it doesn't compose well because there is no way to project <code>MaybeUninit</code> fields as far as I'm aware—again if the parent struct also follows this strategy because it also wants to be pinned now you've got two layers of <code>MaybeUninit</code> fields.</p>
<p>You could also probably do the same thing more safely with a <code>Pin&lt;&amp;mut Option&lt;Bar&gt;&gt;</code> field, but I believe the same downsides apply.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>(<a href="https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2024&amp;gist=d8bfb59dc899bcacaea60b85050fb246" rel="noreferrer">Playground</a>)</p>
<p>It's also possible to have a separate &quot;start&quot; method for some APIs, as in <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/a/79791894/1505451">this answer</a>. But that is also inconvenient for the user, and allows the struct to have a visible &quot;not yet ready&quot; state. I suspect there is no way to avoid &quot;not yet ready&quot; in some form or another if you also want to avoid the <code>Box</code> allocation, but I'm wondering whether there is a more convenient choice I haven't yet thought of.</p>


