Task: Is data race between processes UB?

 <p>Is data race undefined behaviour only for two threads within same process, or is it UB also between processes?</p>
<p>Definition of Data Race from <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/nomicon/races.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Rustonomicon</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Safe Rust guarantees an absence of data races, which are defined as:</p>
<ul>
<li>two or more threads concurrently accessing a location of memory</li>
<li>one or more of them is a write</li>
<li>one or more of them is unsynchronized</li>
</ul>
<p>A data race has Undefined Behavior, and is therefore impossible to perform in
Safe Rust.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The above language refers to threads, but it is not clear whether it means threads within the same process, or whether it can also apply to threads from different processes sharing memory through e.g., shm.</p>
<p>If I would interpret the above strictly, it would mean that I am never allowed to try to read a shared memory that might get modified by some other process while I am reading. This seems quite restrictive.</p>
<p>Is it the case? If so, it would prevent e.g., implementation of non-blocking single producer multiple consumer IPC ring buffer:</p>
<h2>Example design of non-blocking SPMC ring buffer</h2>
<p>Let's have two structs, <code>Writer</code> and <code>Reader</code> sharing memory and sharing <em>writers</em> position:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>pub struct Writer {
    size: usize, // size of the ring buffer in bytes, multiple of 64
    buf: *mut u8, // pointer to shared memory buffer, zeroed at init
    pos: *mut AtomicUsize, // position to be written
    _shm: Shm,
}

pub struct Reader {
    size: usize, // size of the ring buffer in bytes, multiple of 64
    pos: usize, // readers position
    buf: *const u8, // pointer to shared memory buffer, zeroed at init
    wpos: *const AtomicUsize, // position to be written by writer
    _shm: Shm,
}
</code></pre>
<p>Let's assume that each message is exactly 64 bytes long: 1 byte flag + 63 bytes of data. Flag = 0 means empty message, flag = 1 means data was written and ready to be read.</p>
<p>Each write takes following steps:</p>
<ol>
<li>Write data.</li>
<li>Set message flag=1.</li>
<li>Move the writer position.</li>
<li>Zero the flag of the next message.</li>
</ol>
<p>Like this:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>pub fn push(&amp;mut self, data: &amp;[u8; 63]) {
    unsafe {
        let pos = self.pos.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
        ptr::copy_nonoverlapping(
            data.as_ptr(),
            self.buf.add(pos%self.size),
            63,
        )

        // set the flag
        self.buf.add(pos%self.size+63).store(1, Ordering::Release);

        pos += 64;
        self.pos.store(pos), Ordering::Relaxed);
        fence(Ordering::Release); // To prevent next write from reordering;

        self.buf.add(pos%self.size+63).store(0, Ordering::Release); // set next flag to 0

    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Now, the reader can try busy loop over the position in ring buffer and:</p>
<ol>
<li>Read the flag.</li>
<li>Read the writers position. If too big, rewind to writers position, forget everything.</li>
<li>If the flag=1, copy data.</li>
<li>Read the writers position. If too big, forget the data and rewind to w riters position.</li>
<li>Return the data and advance.</li>
</ol>
<p>when it encounters 1, it know there is a message to read. It must check writers position first though, to make sure that it didn't overflow.</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>pub fn read() -&gt; Option&lt;[u8; 63]&gt; {
    unsafe {
        let buf: [u8; 63] = std::mem::MaybeUninit::uninit();
        let flag = self.buf.add(self.pos%self.size + 63).load(Ordering::Acquire);
        let mut wpos = self.wpos.load(Ordering::Acquire);
        if wpos - self.pos &gt; self.size {
            self.pos = wpos; // rewind to the writer's position
            return None; // we lost some messages
        }
        if flag == 0 {
            return None; // no new message there
        }

        ptr::copy_nonoverlapping(
            self.buf.add(pos%self.size),
            buf.as_mut_ptr() as *mut u8,
            63,
        ); // might get corrupted in the process

        fence(Ordering::Acquire); // to prevent the previous copy from reordering
        // load the wpos second time to check that corruption didn't occur
        wpos = self.wpos.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
        if wpos - self.pos &gt; self.size {
            self.pos = wpos; // rewind to the writer's position
            return None; // we lost some messages
        }

        self.pos += 64;
        return Ok(buf.assume_init());
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Naively, the above seems like something that should work at least in assembly. Is it sound in Rust?</p>


