Task: Multiplication issue with custom fixed point number, solution or alternative

 <p>I am not fond of floating point numbers and so have decided to make a custom fixed point number type that I can use for everything that doesn't strictly require floats. Unfortunately this task is not as straight forward as I would have hoped.</p>
<p>The fairly simple solution that we have so far is to simply store a number as an i32 value and treat the first four places as though they were decimal places. For example if we wanted to store 54 we would internally store the number as 540000 as an i32 and if we wanted to convert it back to an integer we would divide it by 10000 to get our integer number.</p>
<p>This is fairly easy to implement and works just fine, however this idea starts to have issues when trying to implement some basic mathematical functions which makes them far less useful to work with.</p>
<p>Addition and subtraction pretty much just work. If we have 37.05 and 0.5 and add them together, behind the scenes it would treat it as 370500 + 5000 which is 375500 and can be treated like 37.55, no issues there.</p>
<p>It is when we get to division, multiplication and a couple others that we start experiencing issues.</p>
<h1>Multiplication</h1>
<p>To make this work theoretically for multiplication is easy enough but in practice doesn't work so great.</p>
<p>What I've tried is this
Number1 * Number2 / 10000
This should get us our answer rather than just multiplying directly because while we know that the first 4 places are decimal, because they are just i32 under the hood it doesn't treat them like that.
To demonstrate 42 * 0.5 should just be 21 right, pretty easy. Except They are stored as 420000 and 5000 which multiplied together gets 2100000000 or if we say the first 4 are decimal 210000 which is why we need to then divide back down to 21. Now this works just fine until we have two numbers which when multiplied together like this exceed the i32 integer limit, because before we divide it back down the numbers are significantly bigger than they are supposed to be and we can't just skip to the correct answer which will fit, I could for this step allocate a bigger number space and then shrink it back down but this seems ineffective and might not fully solve the issue.</p>
<p>I have considered making an iterative function that performs long multiplication step by step but ideally I don't need an iterative function for this process.</p>
<h1>Division</h1>
<p>I think I have division working with the following function which does a step by step long division on the numbers, but ideally this could be improved upon instead of having an iterative process</p>
<pre><code>//this function is designed to work for multiple scales which is why the inputs are i64, and the scale lets us change how many decimal places there are
//The i64 values have to be imputed as the internal values so 5.5 should be 55000
pub fn long_div(num:i64,div:i64,scale:u32) -&gt; i64 {
    let mut res = num/div;
    let mut sca = scale;
    //calculate remainder not handled by direct division
    let mut rem = num%div;
    //iterate over the remainder while reducing the scale for long divison
    while rem!=0 &amp;&amp; sca &gt; 0 {
        sca = sca/10;
        rem = rem*10;
        res += rem/div*sca as i64;
        rem = rem%div;
    }
    return res;
}
</code></pre>
<p>Sorry that my code isn't super easy to read</p>
