Task: Is it safe to update an UnsafeCell while holding an &amp;T reference?

 <p>I have a rust program where:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>I only use one thread to run my entire application. <code>#[tokio::main(flavor = &quot;current_thread&quot;)]</code>. I never spawn new threads only via tokio.</p>
</li>
<li><p>I hold all my models in memory (RAM) for the entire duration of the program. As a result I leak my models with:</p>
</li>
</ol>
<pre><code>pub struct Leaked&lt;T&gt;(UnsafeCell&lt;*mut T&gt;);

impl&lt;T&gt; Leaked&lt;T&gt; {
    pub fn new(value: T) -&gt; Self {
        // Leak it on purpose
        let ptr = Box::into_raw(Box::new(value));
        Self(UnsafeCell::new(ptr))
    }

    pub fn as_mut_ptr(&amp;self) -&gt; *mut T {
        unsafe {
            debug_assert!((*self.0.get()).is_null() == false, &quot;Leaked pointer is null!&quot;);
            *self.0.get()
        }
    }

    pub fn as_ptr(&amp;self) -&gt; *const T {
        self.as_mut_ptr()
    }

    // Do not hold 2 mutable references otherwise it is UB!
    pub fn get_mut_unsafe(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;mut T {
        unsafe { &amp;mut *self.as_mut_ptr() }
    }

    pub fn get_unsafe(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;T {
        unsafe { &amp;*self.as_mut_ptr() }
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Because my appliation runs on one thread I also have:</p>
<pre><code>unsafe impl &lt;T:Send&gt;Send for Leaked&lt;T&gt;{}

unsafe impl &lt;T:Sync&gt;Sync for Leaked&lt;T&gt;{}

impl &lt;T&gt;Clone for Leaked&lt;T&gt;{
    fn clone(&amp;self) -&gt; Self {
        unsafe {
            Self(UnsafeCell::new(*self.0.get()))
        }
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>So cloning is extremely cheap and I do not need Arc. But from studdying rust I have learned that it is unsafe to update an UnsafeCell value meanwhile holding a &amp;T reference. In other words this is technically UB:</p>
<pre><code>pub struct Person {
    pub first_name: String,
    pub age: u8
}

pub fn foo(person: Leaked&lt;Person&gt;) {
    let p: &amp;Person = person.get_unsafe();
    println!(&quot;first name: {}&quot;, p.first_name.as_str());

    // now update via pointer
    unsafe {
        let ptr: *mut Person = person.as_mut_ptr();
        (*ptr).first_name.push_str(&quot;Name is modified!&quot;);
    }

    // is this safe? It could read the old value correct?
    println!(&quot;first name: {}&quot;, p.first_name.as_str());
}
</code></pre>
<p>So technically its UB? I have run that in a hot loop and it still works fine. I know that technically the compiler can keep that on cache and display the old value but in reality how unsafe is it? I have it seen fail when I have a <code>&amp;mut T</code> and <code>&amp;T</code> refernce but it has never failed when I hold <code>&amp;T</code> references and I only update via pointer with UnsafeCell. Or maybe it is unsafe because in the future it will fail once the compiler has more agressive optimisations?</p>


