Task: Derive macro and trait: refer to concrete fn, don&#39;t recurse

 <p>I'm writing a derive proc-macro that automatically implements certain trait:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>trait Foo {
    fn go(&amp;self);
}
</code></pre>
<p>Now given the following:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>#[derive(Foo)]
struct ConcreteFoo;

impl ConcreteFoo {
    pub const fn go(&amp;self) {
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>it generates this:</p>
<pre><code>impl Foo for ConcreteFoo {
    fn go(&amp;self) {
        self.go();
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>which works fine. But if I forget to implement <code>const fn go(&amp;self)</code> on <code>ConcreteFoo</code> (or even make a typo in the fn name) the macro still works, and the function crashes (stackoverflow) at runtime, because it tries to recursively call itself infinitely many times.</p>
<p>If I try to do this directly (without the macro) the compiler will warn me with <code>function cannot return without recursing</code> on the impl. But I don't get that warning/error with the derive macro.</p>
<p>How can I detect this situation? Or: how can I force this:</p>
<pre><code>impl Foo for ConcreteFoo {
    fn go(&amp;self) {
        self.go();
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>to always call <code>go()</code> from the <code>ConcreteFoo</code> and throw a compile error if it doesn't exist? I've tried changing this to <code>ConcreteFoo::go(self);</code> but it doesn't change anything, it still picks up the <code>Foo::go</code> if <code>ConcreteFoo::go</code> is missing.</p>
<p><strong>// EDIT:</strong> So I've found one way to deal with this problem. We can generate a module where the trait is not in the scope. Put the concrete struct in. And create an intermediate function. Like this:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>mod _tmp {
    use super::ConcreteFoo;

    #[inline]
    pub fn go(inst: &amp;ConcreteFoo) {
        // The trait is not in the scope here. It won't
        // ever get picked.
        inst.go();
    }
}

impl Foo for ConcreteFoo {
    fn go(&amp;self) {
        _tmp::go(self);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>It kind of works, but it has other issues, e.g. I'm not sure how to import into the nested mod only those things that I need. Which is necessary for example for generic constraints (in the real code both the trait and the concrete struct can be generic types, the code here is a simplification).</p>


