<pre><code>#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct ResourceRef&lt;'a, R: Resource&gt;
    where R::DynamicType: 'a + Default
{
    type_: PhantomData&lt;R&gt;,
    dynamic_type: R::DynamicType,
    group: Option&lt;Cow&lt;'a, str&gt;&gt;,
    kind: Cow&lt;'a, str&gt;,
    name: String,
}

impl &lt;R: Resource&gt; ResourceRef&lt;'_, R&gt;
    where R::DynamicType: 'static + Default
{
    pub fn new(resource: R) -&gt; Self {
        let name = resource.meta().name.as_deref().expect(&quot;Resource must have a name&quot;);
        Self::new_named(name)
    }

    pub fn new_named(name: &amp;str) -&gt; Self {
        let dynamic_type = R::DynamicType::default();
        let group = R::group(&amp;dynamic_type);
        let group = if group.is_empty() {
            None
        } else {
            Some(group)
        };
        let kind = R::kind(&amp;dynamic_type);

        // ERROR here:
        // cannot return value referencing local variable `dynamic_type` [E0515]
        // returns a value referencing data owned by the current function
        Self {
            type_: PhantomData,
            dynamic_type,
            group: group.clone(),
            kind: kind.clone(),
            name: name.to_string(),
        }
    }

    pub fn group(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;str {
        self.group.as_ref()
    }

    pub fn kind(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;str {
        self.kind.as_ref()
    }

    pub fn name(&amp;self) -&gt; &amp;str {
        &amp;self.name
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>I know something has to be done with the lifetimes to indicate that the <code>DynamicType</code> has the same lifetime as the <code>group</code> and <code>kind</code> fields. I could defer the calculation into the getters, but then that leaves things hanging. I'd rather not allocate a <code>String</code> for each of these.</p>
<p>What is the magic sauce here?</p>


