Task: Unexpected thread blocking during spawned tokio file read

 <p>I'm experiencing unexpected behaviour during a file read using tokio's async I/O API.</p>
<p>I've optimized file reading in the following manner: Any time I read data I</p>
<ol>
<li>await a pending join handle that returns the result of reading from a file</li>
<li>spawn a new file read and store the new handle</li>
<li>return the result from the previous handle</li>
</ol>
<p>The expectation is that this reduces file reading overhead to near zero in my request-response style chunked file transfer over a network, because on every send the data has had ample time to be read into my buffer(s). This works, in theory.</p>
<p>In practice, on a single threaded tokio runtime, I can see in my traces that async work is stalled until the (eager) file read is done, even though that file read is spawned, not awaited:</p>
<p><a href="https://i.sstatic.net/e85UiGiv.png" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.sstatic.net/e85UiGiv.png" alt="send action is stalled" /></a></p>
<p>Not exactly reproducible, but the way my logic works here (and which spans are seen in the screenshot), can be gleaned from this code:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>    #[instrument(skip_all, level = &quot;trace&quot;)]
    pub(super) async fn read(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Option&lt;Result&lt;(usize, &amp;Chunk), Error&gt;&gt; {
        let current_span = Span::current();
        let prepared_read_span = span!(parent: &amp;current_span, Level::TRACE, &quot;prepared read&quot;);
        let preload_next_span = span!(parent: &amp;current_span, Level::TRACE, &quot;preloading next chunk&quot;);
        async move {
            match self.pending_read.take() {
                Some(handle) =&gt; {
                    let (mut file, mut buffer, read_res) =
                        handle.await.expect(&quot;Pending task to complete&quot;);
                    self.swap(&amp;mut buffer).await;
                    if let Ok(bytes_read) = read_res {
                        if bytes_read &gt; 0 {
                            self.pending_read = Some(tokio::spawn(
                                async move {
                                    // Do not spawn in the current span, as this is an eager preload
                                    let read_res = file.read(&amp;mut **buffer.as_mut()).await;
                                    (file, buffer, read_res)
                                }
                                .instrument(preload_next_span),
                            ));
                        }
                    }
                    Some(read_res.map(|bytes_read| (bytes_read, &amp;*self.lazy_buffer)))
                }
                None =&gt; None,
            }
        }.instrument(prepared_read_span).await
    }
</code></pre>
<p>I was thinking, maybe I'm just awaiting things in the wrong order. But, sure enough, on the multi-threaded runtime the same code leads to a better picture:</p>
<p><a href="https://i.sstatic.net/Jf5Bon52.png" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.sstatic.net/Jf5Bon52.png" alt="not stalled on multi-threaded runtime" /></a></p>
<p>The only explanation I have for this is that, even though I'm using tokio's supposedly async API, this is still blocking my (single) async worker thread, somehow. Do you have any explanation for this?</p>
<p>Since this question has been closed, let me explain why this is <em>not</em> a duplicate:</p>
<p>The other question that was marked as duplicate is about the <em>purpose</em> of async I/O. That is quite clear. This is about it not working.</p>
<p>As pointed out by answers to the other question, async I/O should be offloaded to the blocking thread pool, so should <em>not</em> block my async workload, which is what I experience. I also <strong>very explicitly</strong> do not <code>await</code> the read, which would cause this delay and make async I/O (a bit more) pointless</p>
<p>Since it seems it hasn't become clear what my issue is, I will post more code in the hopes to show what I intend to do</p>
<p>Here is the full logic of my file reader. Again, the purpose of the entire thing is to eagerly preload bits from a file, so that they are immediately available when actually needed:</p>
