Task: UdpSocket drops packets with low read_timeout

 <p>I'm using Rust's std <code>UdpSocket</code> to send data from one socket to another one locally.
It all works fine if I set no read timeout or if I set a &quot;big&quot; read timeout like 10ms. Once I set the timeout to a low value, messages seem to get lost if they are received in the same moment the timeout occurs. Here is a simple example so you can reproduce the issue (I have only tested this on Windows - maybe it behaves differently on Linux):</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>    let sender = UdpSocket::bind(&quot;[::1]:3400&quot;).unwrap();
    let receiver = UdpSocket::bind(&quot;[::1]:3401&quot;).unwrap();
    receiver
        .set_read_timeout(Some(Duration::from_micros(10)))
        .unwrap();
    let running = Arc::new(AtomicBool::new(true));
    let r = Arc::clone(&amp;running);
    let (tx, rx) = mpsc::channel();

    let server_task = std::thread::spawn(move || {
        let mut buf = [0; 1024];
        while r.load(Ordering::Relaxed) {
            let res = receiver.recv_from(&amp;mut buf);
            match res {
                Ok((size, _)) =&gt; tx.send(size).unwrap(),
                Err(e) =&gt; {
                    if e.kind() == std::io::ErrorKind::TimedOut {
                        continue;
                    } else {
                        panic!(&quot;ERRROOSS{:?}&quot;, e);
                    }
                },
            };
        }
    });

    sender.connect(&quot;[::1]:3401&quot;).unwrap();
    for _i in 0..1000 {
        sender.send(b&quot;1&quot;).unwrap();
        rx.recv().unwrap();
    }
    running.store(false, Ordering::Relaxed);
    server_task.join().unwrap();
</code></pre>
<p>As you can see in my example I only ever send a new message when the previous one is received. So there is no reason for any buffer to be filled. Also, it works perfectly fine if I increase the timeout.</p>
<p>I know that in a production build a low timeout such as 10 microseconds (although I noticed the issue up to single digit milliseconds as well) wouldn't make any sense in most cases anyways. I wanted to use this to speed up my tests and benchmarks so I can quickly stop them by setting the <code>running</code> <code>AtomicBool</code> to false.</p>
<p>Why does this happen? Am I doing something wrong? I know UDP is not reliable and I always need to expect a packet loss but this issue is very reproducable locally often within just a few messages and only with low timeout values.
Is there a better alternative to &quot;stopping&quot; the recv call on a UdpSocket in sync code (no tokio - only multithreading).</p>


