Task: An enum with associated index and data for each variant

 <p>I am new to Rust, and I am trying to learn the language by solving puzzles on coding sites. For this reason, I can't use external crates, and I need a solution which relies only on the standard library.</p>
<p>My use case is as follows. I need to have a <code>Direction</code> type which has one of 4 possible values: <code>North</code>, <code>East</code>, <code>South</code>, and <code>West</code>. I need to have a method to rotate each direction by a specified multiple of 90 degrees. For example, rotating <code>North</code> by 2 would give <code>South</code>, and rotating <code>East</code> by 3 would give <code>North</code>. In addition, each value has a <code>(i32, i32)</code> tuple associated with it:</p>
<pre><code>North - (0, 1),
East - (1, 0),
South - (0, -1),
West - (-1, 0)
</code></pre>
<p>This sounds like a good candidate for using an enum where each variant would have an associated index: <code>North - 0, East - 1, South - 2, West - 3</code>. Rotation can easily be implemented with modular arithmetic, and the 4 tuples can be stored in an array and accessed using the variant's index. I am more familiar with the concept of enums in Java or Python where each variant can have associated data, and implementing my idea would be easy. For example, in Python:</p>
<pre class="lang-py prettyprint-override"><code>_directions = (
    (0, 1),   # NORTH
    (1, 0),   # EAST
    (0, -1),  # SOUTH
    (-1, 0)   # WEST
)

class Direction(Enum):
    NORTH = 0
    EAST = 1
    SOUTH = 2
    WEST = 3

    @property
    def direction(self) -&gt; tuple[int, int]:
        return _directions[self.value]

    def rotate(self, turns: int) -&gt; 'Direction':
        return Direction((self.value + turns) % 4)
</code></pre>
<p>From what I learned, in Rust, each enum variant is like a new type completely (except it still has the enum's type), so I can't write something like:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>enum Direction {
    North(0),
    East(1),
    South(2),
    West(3),
}
</code></pre>
<p>I can write:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>enum Direction {
    North(u32),
    East(u32),
    South(u32),
    West(u32),
}
</code></pre>
<p>But now each variant can be constructed with any <code>u32</code>, and the indices aren't associated with the variants anymore. I thought I could try to use unit variants:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>enum Direction {
    North = 0,
    East = 1,
    South = 2,
    West = 3,
}
</code></pre>
<p>While this allows me to easily cast an enum variant to <code>usize</code>, I found that casting an integer into an enum is difficult without unsafe code or external crates, and this ability is necessary to implement the <code>rotate</code> method. I could use a match statement or an array to map 0-3 to the enum's variants, but both of these approaches would not scale well if I had more than 4 variants in the enum. In addition, both approaches require me to manually map the given integer to the corresponding direction, which means that if I change the order of the variants, I need to update it in the method that maps int to enum too.</p>
<p>I thought that maybe enums aren't the right tool for my use case, and I need a struct with constant instances defined:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>#[derive(Debug, Default, Hash, Copy, Clone, Eq, PartialEq)]
pub struct Direction(u32);

impl Direction {
    const DIRECTIONS: [(i32, i32); 4] = [(0, -1), (1, 0), (0, 1), (-1, 0)];

    pub const NORTH: Self = Self(0);
    pub const EAST: Self = Self(1);
    pub const SOUTH: Self = Self(2);
    pub const WEST: Self = Self(3);

    pub fn new(turns: u32) -&gt; Self {
        Self(turns % 4)
    }

    pub fn value(self) -&gt; u32 {
        self.0
    }

    pub fn rotate(self, turns: u32) -&gt; Self {
        Self::new(self.0 + turns)
    }

    pub fn direction(self) -&gt; (i32, i32) {
        Self::DIRECTIONS[self.0 as usize]
    }
}

impl From&lt;u32&gt; for Direction {
    fn from(turns: u32) -&gt; Self {
        Self::new(turns)
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>This implementation always works as expected, but the problem with this approach is that the compiler doesn't know that there are only 4 possible values, so a match statement like:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>match d {
    Direction::NORTH =&gt; go_north(),
    Direction::EAST =&gt; go_east(),
    Direction::SOUTH =&gt; go_south(),
    Direction::WEST =&gt; go_west(),
}
</code></pre>
<p>doesn't compile. Is there a way to tell the compiler that a struct can only have a finite number of possible values, like enums, so that match statements are exhaustive?
Alternatively, is there an easier way to use an enum to implement my direction type?</p>
<p><strong>Edit:</strong> I read <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28028854/how-do-i-match-enum-values-with-an-integer">this question</a> which is similar to mine. However, all the answers there use long match statements or arrays, external crates, unsafe code and transmuting or complex macros which look like cumbersome solutions to convert an integer into a type which is already an integer under the hood.</p>


