Task: Is it UB to twice drop the same value of a type for which needs_drop() returns false?

 <p>Basically, the question is in the title. Assume we have a type <code>T</code>, for which <code>std::mem::needs_drop::&lt;T&gt;() == false</code>. Is it UB to drop twice a value of type <code>T</code>?</p>
<p>Here's an example: Consider the following function:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>unsafe fn foo&lt;T&gt;(mut value: Box&lt;T&gt;) {
    if !std::mem::needs_drop::&lt;T&gt;() {
        std::ptr::drop_in_place(&amp;mut *value);
        std::ptr::drop_in_place(&amp;mut *value);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Is it sound?</p>
<p><strong>Edit</strong> As pointed out by interjay, the doc seems to indicate that <code>drop_in_place()</code> only drops the value if <code>needs_drop()</code> returns false. Instead, consider the function</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>unsafe fn foo&lt;T&gt;(mut value: Box&lt;T&gt;) {
    if !std::mem::needs_drop::&lt;T&gt;() {
        drop(std::ptr::read(&amp;mut *value));
        drop(std::ptr::read(&amp;mut *value));
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>While this example is quite artificial, I have encountered some cases where using this property, if it indeed holds, would allow a significantly faster implementation in the case <code>needs_drop::&lt;T&gt;() == false</code> when writing unsafe code.</p>
<p>My problem in &quot;testing&quot; this is that I might miss some exotic type. I'm pretty sure that it is sound if <code>T: Copy</code>. Moreover, miri also does not raise an error when running the test</p>
