Task: What is the recommended way to append a path to Windows&#39; `PATH` environment variable via Rust?

 <p>I'm writing a crude little installer in Rust for a program I've been working on, and it mostly works; however, I've been having some issues with getting the Windows build to modify the system's <code>PATH</code> environment variable rather than the process'.</p>
<p>Here's what I have right now (based on <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/env/fn.join_paths.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">the example given in the docs</a>):</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>fn add_to_path&lt;P&gt;(path: P) -&gt; std::io::Result&lt;()&gt;
where
    P: AsRef&lt;std::path::Path&gt;,
{
    let path_var = std::env::var_os(&quot;PATH&quot;).ok_or_else(|| {
        std::io::Error::new(
            std::io::ErrorKind::NotFound,
            &quot;couldn't find the PATH environment variable&quot;,
        )
    })?;

    let mut paths = Vec::new();
    for p in std::env::split_paths(&amp;path_var) {
        if p == path {
            // `path` is already in PATH, so no work needs to be done
            return Ok(());
        }
        paths.push(p);
    }

    paths.push(path.to_path_buf());
    let path_var = std::env::join_paths(paths).map_err(std::io::Error::other)?;
    unsafe {
        std::env::set_var(&quot;PATH&quot;, &amp;path_var);
    }

    Ok(())
}
</code></pre>
<p>This only modifies <code>PATH</code> for the installer process, not for the system as a whole. The docs for <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/env/fn.set_var.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>std::env::set_var</code></a> seem to back that up:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Sets the environment variable <code>key</code> to the value <code>value</code> for the currently running process.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I looked through the docs for <a href="https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/os/windows/index.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>std::os::windows</code></a> in hopes of finding an alternative that does what I want, but I couldn't seem to find anything. The one idea I have is to run the <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/administration/windows-commands/setx" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>setx</code></a> command in a shell, but that seems kind of sketchy. Is there really no way to do this directly?</p>


