 <p>I am designing a programming language and I have implemented Haskell's Higher Kinded Types(called type constructors in my language) among the feature set of my language, but I am having a hard time seeing the <em>practical applications</em> of the feature (Practical applications in this context means an application that isn't already conveniently implemented with existing language features). I am aware of the following uses such like the following I noted down:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Enforcing type constructor constraint with an unknown number of type arguments (Practical but lacks the application aspect)</p>
</li>
<li><p>Abstracting over types with functors, applicatives and monads (I would like to see an example code where this is useful)</p>
</li>
<li><p>Higher kinded data (I honestly have no understanding of this)</p>
</li>
<li><p>Flattened type argument passing (Seemed nice when my language's type argument entry syntax used angle braces but no longer needed with the change to square braces)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3>Context</h3>
<p>My language supports contracts and impls (similar to Rust's trait and impls) and what I call constraint application which I believe are necessary tools to work with HKTs. Here is my languages code syntax that supports Higher Kinded Types defining the functor contract with type constructors maybe and hashMap implementing the functor contract and a constraint application example -It is set to rust in the code block because rust's syntax closely resembles my language to help with syntax highlighting:</p>
<pre><code>contract[type Self[?], type A] functor {
    // fmap :: f a -&gt; (a -&gt; b) -&gt; f b
    fn fmap[type B](type Self[A] self, type fn(A)B fcn) type Self[B]

    // (-&gt;) :: f a -&gt; a -&gt; f b
    // fn #misc::operator %&gt; [type B](type Self[A] self, type A a) type Self[B] -- Has no actual use
}
// typescope defines the type scope of a type and uses an open system that allows a type's functionality to be extended
typescope hashMap[type Key, type Value] {
    impl[hashMap[Key, ?], Value] functor {
        fn fmap[type B](type hashMap[Key, Value] self, type fn(Value)B fcn) type hashMap[Key, B] {
            (&amp;self).iter().map(fcn).collect()
        }
    }
}
typescope maybe[type T] {
    impl[maybe, T] functor {
        fn fmap[type B](type maybe[T] self, type fn(T)B fcn) type maybe[B] {
            self =&gt; some {
                type maybe(fcn(some))
            }else
        }
    }
}

// Constraint application starts with the `apply` reserved identifier followed by a comptime expression
// `impls[T[?]] functors` is an operation that simply reads: Does `T[?]` implement a contract by the name of `functor`
fn example[type T[?], type A, type B](type T[A] x, type fn(A)B fcn) type T[B] apply impls[T[?]] functor {
    x.fmap(fcn)
}
</code></pre>
